Accidental Release Prevention Program and Chemical-Specific Prevention Steps

Prevention of accidental ammonia and sulfur dioxide releases at The Wine Group?s Franzia Winery Tulare facility is accomplished through sound industry practice in the original ammonia refrigeration system and sulfur dioxide system design and construction (i.e. double-block scenario relief valves, ASME cylinders), the specification and review of system modifications, and the day-to-day operation and maintenance of the system.  
This includes:
?    Compliance with industry standards and codes in effect at the time of initial construction and modification;
?    Performance of a thorough Process Hazard Analyses (PHAs) at least once every five years using accurate Process Safety Information; 
?    Implementation of Operating Procedures which have been reviewed by PHA; 
?    Appropriate initial and refresher training of system operations and maintenance personnel;  
?    Performance of preventive and corrective maintenance according to system component manufacturer recommendations and pursuant to site wide hazardous energy lockout and hot work permit programs;
?    Application of established auditing, inspection, and pre-start-up review protocols; and
?    Use of qualified contractors for work on the system.

Five Year Accident History

Between June 1999 and the present, there have reportedly been no ammonia or sulfur dioxide releases resulting in onsite or off-site injuries, deaths, or property damage, or in off-site environmental damage, evacuations, or sheltering in place.  It is noted that a near miss incident of a condensor fan blade failure in September 2004 had a potential for a release.

